	<li class="comment even depth-3" id="comment-3396">
	<article >

		
		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/582b66ad5ae1b69c7601a990cb9a661a?s=48&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/582b66ad5ae1b69c7601a990cb9a661a?s=96&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' loading='lazy'/><span itemprop="name"><a href="http://josephscott.org/" class="comment-author-link" rel="external nofollow" itemprop="url">Joseph Scott</a></span> 			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2014-03-10T20:40:00-07:00" itemprop="datePublished"><a href="https://blog.sucuri.net/2014/03/more-than-162000-wordpress-sites-used-for-distributed-denial-of-service-attack.html#comment-3396">March 10, 2014</a></time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>You could do something very simple that just disables Pingbacks and not all of XML-RPC.  Something like this should work ( not tested ):</p>
<p>add_action( &#8216;xmlrpc_call&#8217;, function( $method ) {<br />
    if ( $method === &#8216;pingback.ping&#8217; ) {<br />
        wp_die( &#8216;No pingbacks&#8217;, &#8216;Pingback is disabled&#8217;, array( &#8216;response&#8217; =&gt; 403 ) );<br />
    }<br />
} );</p>
<p>There should be no need to hack core WordPress or disable all of XML-RPC.</p>
		</div>

		
		
	</article>
	</li><!-- #comment-## -->

