	<li class="comment odd alt depth-2" id="comment-3401">
	<article >

		
		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/2025929025b4492c58961f28cc4ed93d?s=48&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/2025929025b4492c58961f28cc4ed93d?s=96&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' loading='lazy'/><span itemprop="name"><a href="http://willnorris.com/" class="comment-author-link" rel="external nofollow" itemprop="url">willnorris</a></span> 			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2014-03-12T12:12:00-07:00" itemprop="datePublished"><a href="https://blog.sucuri.net/2014/03/more-than-162000-wordpress-sites-used-for-distributed-denial-of-service-attack.html#comment-3401">March 12, 2014</a></time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>unchecking &#8220;Allow link notifications from other blogs&#8221; will certainly turn off pingbacks for future posts, though you would still need to go in and edit existing posts to disable it for them (bulk edit is your friend here).  Filtering &#8216;xmlrpc_methods&#8217; is just a much faster way to disable pingbacks site-wide.</p>
<p>The &#8220;Attempt to notify any blogs linked to from the article&#8221; controls whether you ping other sites that you&#8217;ve linked to in your posts.  It still generates network traffic to those sites, but cannot be triggered remotely as this article is discussing.  Leaving this enabled is fine.</p>
		</div>

		
		
	</article>
	<ul class="children">

	<li class="comment even depth-3" id="comment-3402">
	<article >

		
		<header class="comment-header">
