		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/a1919d8c618a0bf23d8f8a442fb9cb3a?s=48&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/a1919d8c618a0bf23d8f8a442fb9cb3a?s=96&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' loading='lazy'/><span itemprop="name"><a href="http://www.marcelopedra.com.ar/blog/" class="comment-author-link" rel="external nofollow" itemprop="url">Marcelo Pedra</a></span> 			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2014-03-12T18:21:00-07:00" itemprop="datePublished"><a href="https://blog.sucuri.net/2014/03/more-than-162000-wordpress-sites-used-for-distributed-denial-of-service-attack.html#comment-5990">March 12, 2014</a></time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>Yesterday I implemented Disable XML-RPC plugin in a couple sites and can confirm that at least JetPack stats are working. Also JetPack Post Views plugin works well too.</p>
<p>I don&#8217;t post items remotely so it looks like it&#8217;s safe to disable XML RPC in this particular type of cases.</p>
<p>Also, in websites where WP is used as a simple CMS, with no posts, just pages, it also should be safe to deactivate.</p>
<p>JetPack is still able to publish to Linkedin, Google+, Facebook and Twitter.</p>
<p>And services like dlvr.it are able to retrieve information to send to social networks.</p>
<p>Everything seems to work ok, yet the XML RPC is disabled as I can test it from <a href="http://xmlrpc.eritreo.it/" rel="nofollow ugc">http://xmlrpc.eritreo.it/</a></p>
<p>Hope this help others.</p>
		</div>

		
		
	</article>
	</li><!-- #comment-## -->

	<li class="comment odd alt depth-5" id="comment-3408">
